WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:26.840
[Amit Varma]: People

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:31.280
[Amit Varma]: who talk about the great potential India has and how we are becoming a younger country

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:37.320
[Amit Varma]: and we have this demographic dividend and so on, miss one important and depressing point.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:44.360
[Amit Varma]: As a society, we actually suppress the potential of half our population. Women in this country

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: are treated as second class citizens. They are not empowered in their childhood and are

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.760
[Amit Varma]: often educated less or worse than their brothers. They are forced to conform to roles that destroy

00:01:54.760 --> 00:02:00.560
[Amit Varma]: their potential. In fact, they're looked upon more as property than as people. And when

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:07.320
[Amit Varma]: women speak up about this, they face an amazing amount of anger from men. Anger. Where is

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.920
[Amit Varma]: this anger coming from?

00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:17.480
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.800
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:26.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. When I first asked the remarkable other team, it's

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:31.720
[Amit Varma]: good to join me on this episode. I told her the subject would be misogyny in entertainment

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and Indian society. Aditi said she wanted a different title. She suggested claiming

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:44.320
[Amit Varma]: our space. My subject was a lament, but hers was also a call to action and couldn't have

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:48.680
[Amit Varma]: been more appropriate. While we were chatting about it at the IBM podcast studio, one of

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:54.760
[Amit Varma]: the producers, Swati Bakshi, also got involved and shared some of her insights. So we improvised

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:59.320
[Amit Varma]: and asked her to also be a guest on the show. Swati is a former journalist who now works

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:04.760
[Amit Varma]: as a producer at IBM and will be taking over producing the show from Abbas Momen, whom

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:10.200
[Amit Varma]: you heard in the last episode, who is leaving the scene and the unseen to take over as producer

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:15.840
[Amit Varma]: of Cyrus Broach's fantastic show, Cyrus Says. I tried to convince Abbas to stay, but he

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:21.640
[Amit Varma]: simply doesn't agree that I'm funnier than Cyrus. Go figure. Anyway, I had an enlightening

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:27.480
[Amit Varma]: conversation with Aditi and Swati. But before we get to that, let's take a commercial break.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:31.000
[Amit Varma]: If this happens to be the only podcast you listen to, well, you need to listen to some

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:36.400
[Amit Varma]: more. Check out the ones from IBM podcast who co produced the show with me. Go to IBM

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:42.040
[Amit Varma]: podcast.com or download the IBM app and you'll find a host of great Indian podcasts that

00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:46.920
[Amit Varma]: cover every subject you could think of. From the magazine I edit, Pragati at ThinkPragati.com,

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:51.920
[Amit Varma]: there is the Pragati podcast hosted by Hamsini Hariharan and Pawan Srinath. There is a brilliant

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:57.200
[Amit Varma]: Hindi podcast, Puliyabazi, hosted by Pranay Koteswamy and Sourabh Chandra. And apart from

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:04.560
[Amit Varma]: these policy podcasts, IBM has shows that cover music, films, finance, sports, sci-fi,

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:11.240
[Amit Varma]: tech and the LGBT community all under one roof, or rather all in one app. So download

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:13.400
[Amit Varma]: the IBM podcast app today.

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Aditi and Swati, welcome to the show.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:19.400
[Unknown]: Thank you, Amit. Hi, Amit. Thank you.

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:22.760
[Amit Varma]: Aditi, in the last show that we did last week, where you spoke about the beginning of your

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:27.960
[Amit Varma]: journey as a stand up comedian, you said something which sort of a light bulb went off in my

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:31.400
[Amit Varma]: head. I mean, it shouldn't be a revelation. And I'm sure it's something that people like

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:36.200
[Amit Varma]: you take for granted. But you spoke about how part of the reason you came on your own

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:39.880
[Amit Varma]: as a comedian as someone who would stand and tell jokes was because you were in the girls

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:46.920
[Amit Varma]: college after a girl school, you went to St. Mary's in Pune and then to Sophia's in Bombay.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:51.600
[Amit Varma]: And because there were girls all around you, you were actually able to get the confidence

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.760
[Amit Varma]: and were given the space to stand up and speak for yourself and build an audience. And your

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.880
[Amit Varma]: point was that if it was a coed environment, the boys would never have let that happen,

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:05.440
[Amit Varma]: because they want to be in charge of everything. And at that point, it struck me that there

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:11.800
[Amit Varma]: is no male comedian anywhere who would say that I got the chance to claim my space, because

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:15.640
[Amit Varma]: I was in an all boys school, because if I was in a coed environment, the girls wouldn't

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:22.560
[Amit Varma]: have let me. No male will ever say that, which kind of, you know, brings us to what I want

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:30.440
[Amit Varma]: to start this episode with is that when we speak about the role of men and women in society

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:36.840
[Amit Varma]: and how it is reflected in attitudes, we are starting at a very unequal spot, where women

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:43.320
[Amit Varma]: have to face a whole bunch of structural obstacles, which men are completely unaware of, like

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:48.360
[Amit Varma]: I was unaware that they could be such a thing till you mentioned it in the last episode

00:05:48.360 --> 00:05:53.560
[Amit Varma]: when it's like, okay, another bulb goes off in your head. So I and you know, when I invited

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:57.760
[Amit Varma]: you to do this specific episode, and we spoke about it, the way I framed it was let's talk

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:02.840
[Amit Varma]: about misogyny and entertainment. And you said no, let's call it claiming your space,

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:06.840
[Amit Varma]: because that's a more positive way. And it's also broader. And, you know, we brought Swati

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:11.080
[Amit Varma]: into the show, because she had a whole bunch of thoughts on that from her experience. So

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:14.880
[Amit Varma]: let's talk about claiming your space. What has the journey been like?

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:21.280
[Guest 1]: A G and you know, that line you said was so true is that we're starting from a grossly

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:26.680
[Guest 1]: unequal. I mean, the finishing the starting line is completely different when it comes

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:34.000
[Guest 1]: to the different genders. And I sort of I remember being in an all girls school and

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.200
[Guest 1]: I think I do this joke in my show right now, which is that in my family, we don't beat

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:46.880
[Guest 1]: girls because they bruise easily. It's much easier to beat a little boy and be like, oh,

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:51.520
[Guest 1]: he fell down from a cycle. That's why he has triangulation marks on his neck. And that

00:06:51.520 --> 00:07:01.440
[Guest 1]: always gets a huge laugh and a huge applause. But it also simply points out the fact that

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:08.880
[Guest 1]: the treatment of girls and boys is unequal and is harmful for both girls and boys. I

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:13.760
[Guest 1]: mean, girls, whether it's just being given a chance to be born, really is a is a sort

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:25.800
[Guest 1]: of mathematical. So I think you're sort of you're playing Russian roulette from the womb.

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:33.200
[Guest 1]: If you happen to be any other gender than male, and we cannot deny that whatever narrative

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:41.120
[Guest 1]: that is currently running the world is male has been defined by heterosexual, to a very

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:49.080
[Guest 1]: large extent, white men. Every other story then or every other voice that speaks up is

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:56.280
[Guest 1]: then trying very hard to have themselves heard in a room that's already full of cacophony

00:07:56.280 --> 00:08:02.800
[Guest 1]: of one story that is trying to keep every other story down. So from the point of just

00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:07.920
[Guest 1]: being born to the point of having access to I mean, I keep thinking about I used to have

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:13.680
[Guest 1]: this cousin who was really into cricket. And I remember because we were told no, no, no,

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:19.240
[Guest 1]: only girls only play badminton, and boys will play cricket. And she I mean, unfortunately

00:08:19.240 --> 00:08:25.760
[Guest 1]: for her got breasts at the age of 12. And that was it. That was the end. No more cricket.

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:32.320
[Guest 1]: No more cricket. No, Mithali Raj. I remember and this is an awkward, embarrassing thing

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:37.240
[Guest 1]: to bring up literally within the first three minutes of this podcast. But I remember when

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:44.920
[Guest 1]: I got my period, I hid it from my family for four months. And that included coming up with

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:50.680
[Guest 1]: such weird devices to stop anyone from knowing because I knew that the moment I told them

00:08:50.680 --> 00:08:55.120
[Guest 1]: that I had my period, it would immediately be now sit with your legs closed. Don't talk

00:08:55.120 --> 00:09:01.680
[Guest 1]: loudly. Don't talk to boys. You can't be you know, doing all these things. I was terrified

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:07.720
[Guest 1]: of the fact that my femaleness had suddenly asserted itself completely out of my control.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:11.080
[Amit Varma]: That's almost incredible awareness for 11 or 12 year old or whatever it was.

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:16.080
[Guest 1]: Gee, I'd seen it just happen with I'd just seen it happen with so many of my classmates

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:20.680
[Guest 1]: who would suddenly become demure, you know, during sports period, who would, you know,

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:25.600
[Guest 1]: be sort of like, constantly be like, shoved aside and hushed aside. I just I was like,

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:31.760
[Guest 1]: I can't let my childhood end. And I sort of, I mean, finally, I sort of came to terms with

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.760
[Guest 1]: it four months later when it got found out. It's not even that I told anybody it got found

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:41.120
[Guest 1]: out. And that was another hugely humiliating experience. Even though I come from a very

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:45.200
[Guest 1]: liberal family, where you know, the other kind would be like better chocolate low now

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:50.560
[Guest 1]: you're a woman. But what chocolate I wanted to run around I wanted to talk to boys I want

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:55.960
[Guest 1]: to laugh loudly with my mouth open. I wanted to do those things. And I just knew at that

00:09:55.960 --> 00:10:02.760
[Guest 1]: age, that I was walking into a disadvantage. And I think that has sort of colored my perceptions

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:07.480
[Guest 1]: of everything that I have done as an adult and as a woman.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:12.040
[Amit Varma]: And Swati I often say, you know, when I write about economics, I say from the economics

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:16.360
[Amit Varma]: perspective that India really inhabits three centuries at the same time, the 19th, the

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:21.360
[Amit Varma]: 20th and the 21st. And that's equally true of social attitudes that we inhabit those

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:26.280
[Amit Varma]: three centuries at the same time. And the journey for you in one sense has been starker

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:31.320
[Amit Varma]: for you know, those of us who are from Bombay or Delhi or whatever, because you actually

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:36.240
[Amit Varma]: come from Lucknow, and you've kind of made that journey from there. What has it been

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:37.920
[Guest 2]: like?

00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:42.920
[Guest 2]: It's quite a journey. And being in Lucknow was a entirely different experience, I would

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:49.000
[Guest 2]: say that Lucknow University is still I think, like you said, is 18th century, I would not

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:58.200
[Guest 2]: even say 19th. I mean, the way men behave with women there. And if you go to the university

00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:06.640
[Guest 2]: without wearing a suit or a dupatta, I mean, it's a scandal. And the way men look at you,

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:12.960
[Guest 2]: they hound you, make comments on you, it's very, very normalized, it's quite normalized.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:14.920
[Guest 2]: And it is seen as a...

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:23.560
[Guest 2]: So the level that it has been normalized is a problem. And it's not, it doesn't stop there.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:30.120
[Guest 2]: It seeps into every aspect of your life and everything that you do. So despite being highly

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:35.320
[Guest 2]: educated and you know, working in one of the best organizations in the world, my experience

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:43.160
[Guest 2]: has always been something that I would, you know, remember as an experience filled with

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:46.920
[Guest 2]: discrimination on various levels and various different forms.

00:11:46.920 --> 00:11:50.800
[Amit Varma]: And just to set the context, what period are we talking about when you were in college

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:52.480
[Guest 2]: in Lucknow?

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:54.360
[Guest 2]: It's still 2003.

00:11:54.360 --> 00:12:00.320
[Amit Varma]: Till 2003. And at what point does it sort of strike you that this is something that

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:03.480
[Amit Varma]: is not normal but normalized?

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:09.600
[Guest 2]: Because even at your home, you are told to present yourself in a particular way because

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:15.520
[Guest 2]: you're a girl and you're grown up. I was, I mean, I became comfortable with my own body

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:21.600
[Guest 2]: after I would say, you know, doing my post graduation in Delhi. Until then, it was a

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:27.360
[Guest 2]: very turbulent phase because when I landed in Delhi from Lucknow, it was a completely

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:36.240
[Guest 2]: different structure of, I would say, the structure of living, commuting, studying, everything

00:12:36.240 --> 00:12:42.040
[Guest 2]: was quite different from Lucknow. And it took a toll on my performance also, I remember.

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:48.880
[Guest 2]: And that's like a blot on my resume till now. Until then, I was like a distinction holder.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:54.080
[Guest 2]: And then suddenly in DU, my percentage went down to 56%. It was like shattered.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.080
[Guest 2]: What was different?

00:12:55.080 --> 00:13:01.040
[Guest 2]: It was a cultural, I don't know, a cultural adjustment coming from a small town in India

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:10.200
[Guest 2]: to a bigger town and then being a girl on your own. The kind of pace Delhi offered me,

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:15.360
[Guest 2]: I was not prepared for that. And the kind of people around, I was not prepared for that.

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:22.040
[Guest 2]: And it took me a lot of time to, you know, sync with the pace of the city. And that was

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:28.440
[Guest 2]: obviously something that I had to understand. And then two years time was something that

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:35.720
[Guest 2]: I took to understand that, to be in sync with myself and the city. So the city in itself

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:41.400
[Guest 2]: is something, a big phenomena that decides how a woman would be. I don't know in other

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:47.720
[Guest 2]: countries also, I think it's the same. But in India, it's very much a big factor that

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:52.320
[Guest 2]: decides how you're going to move, till what time you're going to move, what subjects are

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:56.640
[Guest 2]: you going to study if you're studying in a university. Because, you know, I remember

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:02.560
[Guest 2]: in Lucknow University, the sociology department was notorious. And there were very few women

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:08.360
[Guest 2]: opting for sociology because of that. One being myself, because my sister, elder sister

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:13.560
[Guest 2]: who was studying in that department, she told me categorically not to take sociology because

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:18.920
[Guest 2]: that department is notorious. So you imagine that how women do not, you know, make their

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:21.440
[Guest 2]: choices, their choices are already being made.

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:26.080
[Amit Varma]: So here's my question for you. That fine, Lucknow and Delhi when you move there were

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:30.360
[Amit Varma]: like 18th century or 19th century India or whatever. And these attitudes were there and

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:34.480
[Amit Varma]: you just had to kind of adjust. But then you went on after that to work for the BBC, for

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:38.240
[Amit Varma]: example. Was that 21st century India?

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:47.240
[Guest 2]: It is. It is because BBC gave me a perspective. I was not that open minded, I would say to

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:51.840
[Guest 2]: discuss certain things that the profession of journalism and the organisation gave me

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:57.240
[Guest 2]: to think about. And the newsroom was a space where we used to discuss each and everything.

00:14:57.240 --> 00:15:03.000
[Guest 2]: And it's a good space to do that. Because there is no filters that we have to apply

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.520
[Guest 2]: when we're discussing in meetings and all those things. But, you know, it took a lot

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:12.440
[Guest 2]: of time for me there also to be comfortable talking about it. Like Aditi now can talk

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:18.760
[Guest 2]: about her periods and I now can, but a few years down the line, I could not actually.

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:25.080
[Guest 2]: So the organisation actually was something that offered me that space where I could open

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:26.480
[Guest 2]: up and explore.

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And would you say it is true of journalism or are there still those misogynistic attitudes

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:35.040
[Amit Varma]: creeping into journalism itself?

00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:39.880
[Guest 2]: I would say true of journalism as a profession, definitely, because, you know, you are given

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:45.000
[Guest 2]: certain assignments like reporting assignments where you are challenged by the space that

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:51.600
[Guest 2]: you are accessing. And you have to understand that how you're going to do keeping yourself

00:15:51.600 --> 00:15:57.720
[Guest 2]: safe at the same time delivering what is required of you. So I would say journalism definitely

00:15:57.720 --> 00:16:03.240
[Guest 2]: made me a stronger person who is not only a woman, but a person.

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:06.120
[Amit Varma]: A stronger person by empowering you or challenging you?

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:11.520
[Guest 2]: Challenging me. Empowerment comes very late, you know, in Delhi, of course, when after

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:17.200
[Guest 2]: 2012 also, when all these steps were taken that people would be dropped off, women would

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:21.720
[Guest 2]: be dropped off with guards and all those things, that things, you think that a city can be

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:26.640
[Guest 2]: secured like that, it's not possible at all, you cannot do that. So empowerment is something

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:32.880
[Guest 2]: that I think our country needs to needs to think about, but challenging, of course, because

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:37.080
[Guest 2]: if you are challenged, then you think about your own security, and then you devise ways

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:42.520
[Guest 2]: of doing it. That is, again, is limiting your choices, because you don't have many choices

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:47.240
[Guest 2]: to you know, to function and to make yourself secured at the same time.

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:52.880
[Amit Varma]: And Mumbai, of course, is a world apart from Delhi. So you started doing, for example,

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:59.240
[Amit Varma]: open mics and stand up comedy in 2010. And on that, was it harder for you to be accepted?

00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:04.920
[Guest 1]: Yeah, because the truth is also that we are taught we are inconveniences, our bodies are

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:09.000
[Guest 1]: inconveniences, the space that we try to occupy is an inconvenience. Every time we speak up,

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:14.680
[Guest 1]: it is an inconvenience. We are collateral damage to the narrative of the great man story.

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:25.960
[Guest 1]: And we are side characters in our own story. And so I think that sense of like worthlessness,

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:30.240
[Guest 1]: that's why it attaches itself to your psyche. That's why it attaches itself to our bodies.

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:35.480
[Guest 1]: That's why I mean, marketers and advertisers can prey on our insecurities left, right and

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:39.920
[Guest 1]: center. I personally do not remember looking at my own body because I was terrified. I

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:43.520
[Guest 1]: was like, I don't know what is happening to my body as I grew up. Because I was like,

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:49.720
[Guest 1]: I know that this is a problem. I know that this is going to like, restrict my space,

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:53.240
[Guest 1]: this is going to make me invisible.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:56.960
[Guest 1]: And so it's going to make you invisible because people will see the body, not the person will

00:17:56.960 --> 00:18:01.920
[Guest 1]: see the body and not the person will not hear the words and that has not stopped. That has

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:06.640
[Guest 1]: not stopped. I mean, I still am constantly getting you know, trash about what I wear

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:14.400
[Guest 1]: on stage. You know, even the way I'm sure no male comedian ever does. No, no, no. You

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:18.720
[Guest 1]: know, the kind of comments that that you see below my YouTube videos, which I've stopped

00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:22.760
[Guest 1]: looking at. But if you see the kind of comments below my YouTube videos, they will have a

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:29.600
[Guest 1]: distinct color that I don't think any male comedian sees under their videos ever. The

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:34.080
[Guest 1]: kind of abuse even if you say something ridiculous and you know, the kind of abuse that comes

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:41.400
