00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:32.080
[Amit Varma]: but in reinforcing that, you know, it's sort of a vicious cycle that plays out. How much

00:34:32.080 --> 00:34:39.280
[Amit Varma]: of a role does popular culture have to play in terms of the role of women in Indian society?

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:45.080
[Amit Varma]: And is that something that has gradually changed? Like, essentially, the reason so many Indian

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:49.280
[Amit Varma]: men end up so entitled and become stalkers of women is because that's what you see in

00:34:49.280 --> 00:34:53.880
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood films. That's how you win a woman's heart by teasing her and harassing her till

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:58.320
[Amit Varma]: she eventually gives in. Is that changing? And how much of a role does popular culture

00:34:58.320 --> 00:34:59.320
[Guest 2]: play in that?

00:34:59.320 --> 00:35:06.400
[Guest 2]: Yeah, definitely. Popular culture itself is a representation of what you see around. If

00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:12.640
[Guest 2]: you see the history of various forms of popular culture, say films, if we see how many women

00:35:12.640 --> 00:35:18.840
[Guest 2]: have given space in history, like you were saying that we have to claim space and you

00:35:18.840 --> 00:35:24.600
[Guest 2]: were mentioning about Tuntun. Do we actually want to know about Tuntun and how many people

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:31.480
[Guest 2]: have written about Tuntun? So that kind of thing that they have been systematically relegated

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:33.640
[Guest 2]: to the margins in every spare.

00:35:33.640 --> 00:35:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, here's a tragedy that, you know, I heard Tuntun's name today just now in the

00:35:37.360 --> 00:35:41.440
[Amit Varma]: podcast when you brought it up after probably decades. And I remembered at the last time

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:45.520
[Amit Varma]: I heard her name, I would, when I was a kid, I would probably have laughed at the thought

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:51.680
[Amit Varma]: of Tuntun. And one should not laugh at the thought of Tuntun. It's incredibly, you know,

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:54.520
[Guest 1]: and everything that, you know, I mean, you think about

00:35:54.520 --> 00:36:00.720
[Guest 1]: someone, but someone as amazing as Shobha Kote, for example, you're like, what a woman,

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:05.920
[Guest 1]: what timing, those scenes that, oh my God, just stellar work. Who's talking about her

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:10.640
[Guest 1]: in comedy? Who is, I mean, even when we went through the history of comedy, there's very

00:36:10.640 --> 00:36:14.840
[Guest 1]: little mention of women. There's very little mention of their contributions. And you know,

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:18.320
[Guest 1]: I agree. I mean, I agree and disagree to a certain extent that because I feel like whenever

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:23.960
[Guest 1]: Bollywood film, then we're like, wow, wow, look, Bollywood is affecting society change.

00:36:23.960 --> 00:36:27.560
[Guest 1]: But then when bad things happen, you're like, well, it's just art. So there has to be a

00:36:27.560 --> 00:36:33.120
[Guest 1]: level of somewhere where responsibilities are taken on both ends, right? By the filmmakers

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:36.760
[Guest 1]: to realize that, okay, we are living in a world where, you know, violence against women

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:41.200
[Guest 1]: is at its peak or is being reported at its peak. And it's something that everybody is

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:46.240
[Guest 1]: talking about and needs to be addressed. So I maybe will not make a rape revenge fantasy

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:51.400
[Guest 1]: film for a man, maybe, you know what I'm saying? As a filmmaker, maybe you decide to take that

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:54.480
[Amit Varma]: responsibility. There was a horrible film which came out last year where Hrithik Roshan

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:59.240
[Amit Varma]: played a blind guy, one of a blind couple and his wife gets raped. And the second time

00:36:59.240 --> 00:37:03.160
[Amit Varma]: she gets raped, she kills herself. And she does it for the reason that she doesn't want

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:08.640
[Amit Varma]: to cause him any more pain because every time she is raped, he is getting caused pain. And

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:12.920
[Amit Varma]: that is just mind blowing. This is a film which came out last year. How can those people

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:17.520
[Guest 1]: even agree to act in those movies? And so there has to be there has to I mean, there

00:37:17.520 --> 00:37:26.440
[Guest 1]: has to be a responsibility taken in both directions. And I mean, truly the we cannot there's that

00:37:26.440 --> 00:37:30.400
[Guest 1]: whole chicken and egg situation where you're like, oh, does the phenomena come first or

00:37:30.400 --> 00:37:35.560
[Guest 1]: the this thing? These are two inextricably tied in to each other. And you attack them

00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:40.320
[Guest 1]: where you can. Yes, exactly. Exactly. It's because and I you know what, this is one thing

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:44.800
[Guest 1]: that I find very amazing is when people are like you comedians, y'all are attacking that

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:52.680
[Guest 1]: movie. I was like, I eat my dinner for lunch the next day. I have worn my pajamas for five

00:37:52.680 --> 00:37:57.800
[Guest 1]: days in a row. You know what I'm saying? That's my level of power. So me saying something

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:04.240
[Guest 1]: stupid to some dumb movie, which is a 60 crore project with 40 crores in this thing you're

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:10.920
[Unknown]: telling me my stupid to have pajamas Salman Khan doesn't even have a shirt. Shame on you,

00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:17.040
[Guest 1]: you privileged person. But you know, we we have stopped acknowledging the unevenness

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:23.440
[Guest 1]: of power. That sort of popular culture because I don't know when popular culture became the

00:38:23.440 --> 00:38:27.600
[Guest 1]: victim. I don't know when Bollywood became the thing to be protected. I don't know when

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:33.160
[Guest 1]: the other day also some that Airtel thing happened where some girl right, you know,

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:40.880
[Unknown]: said some nonsense. Somebody was like, I feel bad for Airtel. I said once you feel bad.

00:38:40.880 --> 00:38:48.560
[Unknown]: I feel bad for Airtel. What? This is a corporate with money with PR with what? And also no

00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:52.920
[Unknown]: matter what has been done to a company should never feel bad for a company. Definitely never

00:38:52.920 --> 00:39:01.560
[Unknown]: ever for a company. That's that's sort of that's my heart beats for relying on Adani

00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:10.120
[Guest 1]: cop must be lying awake in bed. Poor Adani cop. You know that that sort of like treating

00:39:10.120 --> 00:39:14.680
[Guest 1]: pop culture as if it's equal to the people who are consuming it is very dangerous. Right?

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:18.640
[Amit Varma]: And it's a vicious circle they feed on each other. Yes, and everything is interrelated.

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:22.160
[Amit Varma]: But you attack them when you can. If you see something wrong, you call it out. Yes. That

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:26.280
[Amit Varma]: doesn't mean you have to call everything that is wrong out. I'm just preempting the inevitable

00:39:26.280 --> 00:39:33.360
[Amit Varma]: what about the Airtel ka naam liya, Hatch ne bhi wo kya, uska naam kyu nahi liya. So

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:37.600
[Amit Varma]: before we started recording this Swati, you were talking about journalism and how it is

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:43.120
[Amit Varma]: such still today such a misogynistic profession and you said something that intrigued me.

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:47.440
[Amit Varma]: You said that even the women who have risen to the top of the profession have turned themselves

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:54.880
[Guest 2]: into men. I'm going to ask you to elaborate on that. Yes. I think my experience I'm talking

00:39:54.880 --> 00:40:02.440
[Guest 2]: only from my experience and I can't talk for others. But my experience has been like that.

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:09.640
[Guest 2]: Because I think that's the way for women to reach to the top. I definitely know that it's

00:40:09.640 --> 00:40:16.680
[Guest 2]: much harder for them than their male colleagues. But then in that, you know, fight, when they

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:21.040
[Guest 2]: become like their male colleagues is something that they're not conscious about.

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:24.720
[Amit Varma]: When you say that's a way for them to reach to the top, you mean play the patriarchal

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:31.020
[Guest 2]: game, do the whining? Yeah, I mean, because there is a lot of fight going on internally

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:36.160
[Guest 2]: and externally, you know, when you're trying to achieve something within a space that has

00:40:36.160 --> 00:40:42.480
[Guest 2]: its set rule, because you cannot change the organizational rule. So you somehow now device

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:50.040
[Guest 2]: ways of dealing with it. And the people that you're dealing with are not easy. Then what

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:56.120
[Guest 2]: happens is your own tools and equipments that you have to fight it out do not feel sufficient,

00:40:56.120 --> 00:41:01.080
[Guest 2]: you have to learn something, do something undo something. And that process actually

00:41:01.080 --> 00:41:08.080
[Guest 2]: changes you before you even realize it that it has, you know, has had an impact on you

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:13.120
[Guest 2]: in a way that you're not recognizing it, but you are completely changed by the time you

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:17.840
[Guest 2]: pass through that entire tunnel and you reach to the target where you wanted to, you are

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:22.320
[Amit Varma]: a completely changed person. So if I can just paraphrase that to make sure I'm understanding

00:41:22.320 --> 00:41:26.120
[Amit Varma]: it correctly, what you mean is that, let's say that you're a journalist, and you have

00:41:26.120 --> 00:41:30.960
[Amit Varma]: great journalistic skills, whatever they are, but that's not all you need to get ahead.

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:35.120
[Amit Varma]: You also have to play that corporate game of getting ahead in the organization according

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:40.120
[Amit Varma]: to certain rules, whether they are certain rules of socializing or certain modes of behavior

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:45.480
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And if you choose to play that game to get ahead in the profession,

00:41:45.480 --> 00:41:50.080
[Amit Varma]: then that will inevitably change you as a person in the process. And you will become

00:41:50.080 --> 00:41:53.840
[Amit Varma]: a part of that game, which is what you mean by the women who reach the top turning into

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:58.880
[Guest 2]: men. Yeah, because you are trying to fit in somewhere and it has its own, you know, set

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:04.680
[Guest 2]: of rules to and consequences to confirm, I mean, rules to confirm to and consequences

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:09.960
[Guest 2]: that will follow. You know that this is the only way. And that is how you decide that

00:42:09.960 --> 00:42:14.680
[Guest 2]: whether I want this or I don't want this, like I made a decision that I don't want this.

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:21.080
[Guest 2]: So I did not have, you know, have to walk that particular road. And I made my alternative

00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:25.960
[Guest 2]: to you know, reach somewhere where I want to see myself. So everybody is not able to

00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:32.760
[Guest 2]: make that. Yes. In a way, I find myself privileged and I'm in complete harmony with myself, no

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:38.800
[Guest 2]: matter what others think about it. You know, in a workspace, when you are not able to follow

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:45.000
[Guest 2]: the rules, you are seen as somebody who is cynical, who is not making enough effort to

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:49.560
[Guest 2]: do something. I have heard from my bosses that, you know, you're very pessimistic and

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:53.160
[Guest 2]: you're a cynical person because you're not there are so many opportunities, you're not

00:42:53.160 --> 00:42:58.440
[Guest 2]: trying to grab them. Because I saw people grabbing those opportunities and the ways

00:42:58.440 --> 00:43:03.080
[Guest 2]: it through which you know, those opportunities can be grabbed. And I'm somebody who decided

00:43:03.080 --> 00:43:09.280
[Guest 2]: that okay, I don't want to be that successful. What success actually means in those terms.

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:14.680
[Guest 2]: So it's okay for me that if I'm not successful, that's the way I am. But people who have actually

00:43:14.680 --> 00:43:20.700
[Guest 2]: achieved it would not admit that, that they have done that. But they would say that these

00:43:20.700 --> 00:43:27.800
[Guest 2]: are the ways to achieve success, because you can't do much about it. It's a constitutional

00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:31.880
[Guest 2]: thing. Like there is a constitution which has already been set. It's not being said

00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:37.600
[Guest 2]: by women, but they have to follow that it's the rule of law, and you live by the rule

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:38.600
[Amit Varma]: of law.

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:43.520
[Amit Varma]: In all fairness, I'll just say that, you know, I write for a number of publications and all

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:47.560
[Amit Varma]: my editors at this current point in time are women and they have reached the top of the

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:52.000
[Amit Varma]: professions and they're very strong women and I respect them a lot. But I can't speak

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:55.160
[Guest 1]: on their behalf. You know, you're sharing your experience. So,

00:43:55.160 --> 00:44:02.000
[Guest 1]: You know, and that's what it is, is that, I mean, because often this, the conversations

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:07.800
[Guest 1]: around patriarchy and misogyny ends up becoming a men versus women thing, which it is not.

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:14.360
[Guest 1]: Women can be misogynistic as well. And I can say safely that, you know, before I sort of

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:20.040
[Guest 1]: got introduced to so many feminist women and feminist thought, I was also a misogynist.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:30.040
[Guest 1]: I was in charge of my own oppression. I internalized my own misogyny to hate myself enough because

00:44:30.040 --> 00:44:37.240
[Guest 1]: I knew that that was what everybody else was doing. And so, you know, when I meet women

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:42.160
[Guest 1]: who are misogynistic, it doesn't surprise me. It just breaks my heart a little bit that

00:44:42.160 --> 00:44:47.840
[Guest 1]: like, you know, this is sort of, I wish I could tell you that this is about, you know,

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:52.040
[Guest 1]: it could free both of us if we stopped thinking like this, but that's not my place.

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:56.160
[Guest 1]: They made the choices. Exactly. And I cannot be the judge of how

00:44:56.160 --> 00:45:02.600
[Guest 1]: they got to making those choices. Yes, if you know, if they are in turn hampering my

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:09.640
[Guest 1]: growth, I can be mad. But that's at the max I can be is mad because it just, I understand

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:14.400
[Guest 1]: that the systems that are oppressing me are the same systems that are oppressing them.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:21.000
[Guest 1]: And with women, I just feel like the conversations you can have are very different. Whereas with

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:26.920
[Guest 1]: men, I have seen an active resistance to understanding. And I mean this in the most like the most

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:31.400
[Guest 1]: well-meaning men will turn around and be like, what you're saying women are discriminated

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:37.560
[Guest 1]: against. That's crazy. I'm like, you're kidding. You're kidding. I have done. I mean, I have

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:41.040
[Guest 1]: to say this. I don't do interviews anymore because it's been a year and a half since

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:45.120
[Guest 1]: I've done an interview. And I just stopped doing them because I was getting calls from

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:49.280
[Guest 1]: female journalists, of course, who would call me and say that the you know, we want to talk

00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:53.000
[Guest 1]: to you about comedy, and then it would just go into but tell us about sexism. And I was

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:58.040
[Guest 1]: like, but I have brilliant thoughts about comedy as well. But to them, they're like,

00:45:58.040 --> 00:46:02.040
[Guest 1]: we're doing you a favor by showcasing you. Yeah, if you wanted to talk about comedy,

00:46:02.040 --> 00:46:08.320
[Guest 1]: we'd call the XYZ. We'd call the men, but we are calling you so now avratas. And so

00:46:08.320 --> 00:46:14.120
[Guest 1]: then you have to avrat them. And so beyond the point, and also I mean, like, to be honest,

00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:22.280
[Guest 1]: you meet sort of interviewers who are so deeply dismissive of the work that you do. I have

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:25.280
[Guest 1]: had to educate all my interview, whenever I get called for an interview, I'm like, have

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:30.520
[Guest 1]: you seen a show? Do you want I'll send you a video so you watch it. So you know what

00:46:30.520 --> 00:46:36.120
[Guest 1]: you're talking about when I give you my free time to come and tell you about my work.

00:46:36.120 --> 00:46:40.120
[Amit Varma]: At this point, Swati, I must confess that when I invited Aditi on the show, I proposed

00:46:40.120 --> 00:46:45.000
[Amit Varma]: two ideas. I said one, we can talk about the history of stand up comedy in India, especially

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:50.920
[Amit Varma]: and two, we can talk about misogyny in entertainment. So it's like talking about me.

00:46:50.920 --> 00:46:56.240
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, you know, again, don't be defensive. Yeah, exactly. And no, and the and you know,

00:46:56.240 --> 00:47:00.180
[Amit Varma]: going on that don't be defensive point. It is also true that whenever you mention misogyny

00:47:00.180 --> 00:47:06.760
[Amit Varma]: to a man, the man will take it as if it is a personal slur and get defensive. And that,

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:12.440
[Amit Varma]: in a sense is also an admission of guilt in a manner of speaking. Yes. Yeah. And I mean,

00:47:12.440 --> 00:47:17.080
[Guest 1]: you know, the thing is, I like we are all misogynist. We have all been misogynist at

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:22.520
[Amit Varma]: some point in time or the other. And misogyny is just one level of f***ed upness. We are

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:27.560
[Amit Varma]: all humans are f***ed up in various different human ways. And it's fine. If you work on

00:47:27.560 --> 00:47:32.920
[Amit Varma]: that and acknowledge that like, when I look back on myself as you know, 15 years ago,

00:47:32.920 --> 00:47:39.960
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't just misogynist. I was a lot else which is you know, you work past that. Yeah.

00:47:39.960 --> 00:47:49.680
[Guest 1]: And and I think we especially with the elite women's right now. We are angry. We're angry.

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:53.880
[Guest 1]: Women are who are realizing their rights. And the way they have been discriminated against

00:47:53.880 --> 00:47:59.360
[Guest 1]: are angry. And I feel like that anger also intimidates people and they will tell you

00:47:59.360 --> 00:48:05.760
[Guest 1]: tone down your anger, be nicer, be more palatable. How much how many waves of feminism will come

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:11.680
[Guest 1]: and go before you will realize that this anger is justified, that this is costing us time,

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:16.560
[Guest 1]: costing us money, costing us emotions, costing us energy, costing us careers, costing us,

00:48:16.560 --> 00:48:20.960
[Guest 1]: you know, families, how much longer and how much more politely would you like someone

00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:26.800
[Amit Varma]: to say, please stop f***ing XYZ over? So what do you answer then be to the question I'd

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:31.560
[Amit Varma]: earlier asked and Swati had taken on that are things getting better within this age

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:36.120
[Guest 1]: of social media and so on? In fact, I think, no, you know, I don't know if they're getting

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:43.640
[Guest 1]: better as an absolute whole. The fields where it can be messed up is even more like, like

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:49.000
[Guest 1]: now the the what used to be these conversations in public spaces like on the roads, where

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.840
[Guest 1]: you're walking down the road and you get cat called and then you suddenly cover yourself

00:48:51.840 --> 00:48:56.280
[Guest 1]: up with your dupatta and you walk a little smaller. Those conversations are being taken

00:48:56.280 --> 00:49:00.320
[Guest 1]: online. Yeah. So now you are sitting at a Twitter account where you've just wanted to

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:05.640
[Guest 1]: say I ate an apple and then suddenly you've got 300 you know abuses under that and so

00:49:05.640 --> 00:49:09.200
[Guest 1]: you realize well I'm not going to come back to this site. I'm not going to say so how

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:14.120
[Guest 1]: do you deal with that you don't read the comments? I personally you know again it took me time

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:20.360
[Guest 1]: it took me time and it requires a lot of sort of it requires a lot of mental energy and

00:49:20.360 --> 00:49:25.360
[Guest 1]: it costs you a lot where you see your male peers shooting off at the mouth and you know

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:29.320
[Guest 1]: getting ahead in life and whatever it is that they're doing. Whereas you are sort of like

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:33.160
[Amit Varma]: no no no I don't know I should cut my back back in front of you you're wearing a backpack

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:39.400
[Guest 1]: in front of you very essentially and it takes time it takes time but I I know for a fact

00:49:39.400 --> 00:49:46.000
[Guest 1]: that this is a thing and that the battle as we explore new fields is not going to become

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:51.960
[Guest 1]: absolutely better. The battle will take different shapes and forms of just being able to protect

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:57.600
[Guest 2]: yourself and being able to be free at the same time. And I think we really need to question

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:06.800
[Guest 2]: women's role also because it's very important to recognize that who is actually playing

00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:13.200
[Guest 2]: an important role in carrying this kind of tradition forward. It's not only men because

00:50:13.200 --> 00:50:20.560
[Guest 2]: it can't happen like that. It's it's definitely males and females both and we have to realize

00:50:20.560 --> 00:50:25.440
[Amit Varma]: it and at some point address it. Wasn't it Kareena Kapoor who recently dismissively said

00:50:25.440 --> 00:50:29.760
[Guest 2]: oh but I'm not a feminist. But I'm not I would not say that I'm a feminist. Yeah well well

00:50:29.760 --> 00:50:34.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean I mean my position there really is that every decent person male or female should

00:50:34.160 --> 00:50:38.120
[Guest 1]: be a feminist should be a feminist. Yeah you know being human. You know but this is another

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:42.480
[Guest 1]: thing. Why is the labor of claiming feminism on Kareena Kapoor. Why does nobody go to Shakti

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:46.680
[Guest 1]: Kapoor and say Bhai tumne toh bahut rape scene ki hai. Tell us are you a feminist. Nobody

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:53.560
